title: Worked Solution
text: To determine whether the value $$y=\frac{4}{3}$$ is a solution to the equation $$9y+2=6y+3$$, we can substitute $$\frac{4}{3}$$ for $$y$$ in the equation and see if it holds true. Substituting $$\frac{4}{3}$$ for $$y$$ in the equation gives us: $$9\left(\frac{4}{3}\right)+2=6\left(\frac{4}{3}\right)+3$$ Simplifying this expression gives us: $$12+2=8+3$$ Which simplifies to: $$14=11$$ Since 14 does not equal 11, $$y=\frac{4}{3}$$ is not a solution to the equation $$9y+2=6y+3$$.
